          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "The Alcazaba of Almería towers over the city from its hilltop perch. Built in 955 by Caliph Abd al-Rahman III, this citadel—Spain's largest after the Alhambra—unfolds across three walled enclosures: the gardens of the first, the five-nave caliphal cistern of the second, and the Christian castle erected by the Catholic Monarchs in 1489.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Step inside the Cathedral of the Incarnation, a unique fortress-temple built after the 1522 earthquake. Its thick walls, battlements, and arrow slits bear witness to attacks by Barbary pirates. Inside, the neoclassical cloister and ambulatory chapels deserve close attention.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Civil War Shelters burrow 9 meters beneath Paseo de Almería. These 4.5-kilometer underground galleries, designed by architect Guillermo Langle Rubio in 1937, could shelter 40,000 residents. The reconstructed operating room is particularly striking.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Cable Inglés, an ore-loading pier built in 1904 in Eiffel-style architecture, juts into the sea from Almadrabillas beach. Declared a Cultural Heritage Site in 1998, it offers beautiful perspectives over the port at sunset.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Make your way to Plaza Vieja, the city's administrative heart. The 19th-century neoclassical town hall borders this shaded square. The Monument to the Martyrs of Liberty at its center commemorates victims of absolutist repression in 1824.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Paseo de Almería connects Puerta de Purchena to the port. This shopping avenue, lined with century-old ficus trees, cuts through downtown and passes above the underground shelters. Café terraces come alive as evening falls.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Walk the waterfront promenade of Parque Nicolás Salmerón to the marina. Palm trees line the path, with the illuminated Alcazaba glowing in the backdrop.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Head to Mercado Central for a tapas crawl. Almería upholds the tradition of free tapas served with every drink—the bars around the market compete in generosity.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Late afternoon swim at El Zapillo beach, Almería's urban beach, with views of the Cable Inglés and the Sierra de Gádor mountains.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
          "to_next_leg": {
