            "map_keywords": [
              "Playa de Mónsul Cabo de Gata",
              "Playa de los Genoveses San José",
              "Arrecife de las Sirenas Cabo de Gata",
              "Faro de Cabo de Gata",
              "San José Cabo de Gata",
              "Las Salinas de Cabo de Gata",
              "Mirador de La Amatista Cabo de Gata"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Mónsul beach is the natural park's most famous stretch. Enormous black lava tongues frame its golden sand—this is where a scene from Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade was filmed. At the beach's center, a massive wind-sculpted rock serves as a landmark.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Want a kilometer of pristine sand? Los Genoveses beach stretches across a bay bordered by dunes, without a single building in sight. The shallow water slopes gently, perfect for swimming. In summer, vehicle access is limited to a few cars per day.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Arrecife de las Sirenas (Mermaid Reef) at the cape's tip owes its name to the monk seals sailors once mistook for mermaids. Dark volcanic chimneys emerge from turquoise waters, right at the foot of the Cabo de Gata lighthouse built in 1863.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The village of San José serves as the park's main gateway. Its white houses and small fishing port live by the rhythm of the seasons. Terraces facing the sea serve fresh fish cuisine.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The Cabo de Gata salt flats extend across 400 hectares between the road and the sea. Over 80 bird species frequent these shallow basins, including flamingos visible from observation posts along the site.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Climb up to Mirador de La Amatista for a plunging view over the volcanic cliffs and Pico de los Frailes, the park's highest point. The violet-hued rocks give the viewpoint its name.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Coastal hike between Genoveses and Mónsul along the ridges. The trail follows the cliffs and crosses several deserted little coves with colorful geological formations—white, orange, gray.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
              "practical_info": {
                "distance": "6 km",
                "duration": "~2h",
                "difficulty": "Moderate"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Snorkeling in the clear waters around San José. Posidonia seagrass meadows shelter wrasses, white seabreams, and octopuses among the volcanic rocks.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Flamingo and black-winged stilt watching at the salt flats, ideally late in the day when the low light colors the basins pink and gold.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 45,
              "practical_info": {
                "best_time": "Late afternoon, 1 hour before sunset",
                "tip": "Binoculars recommended"
              }
            }
          ],
          "to_next_leg": {
