            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Seville Cathedral is the world's largest Gothic cathedral. Construction began in 1403 on the site of the former Almohad mosque, preserving the Patio de los Naranjos with its 60 orange trees. Inside, Christopher Columbus's tomb—repatriated from Havana—rests on the shoulders of four bronze bearers.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Climb the 35 ramps of La Giralda, a 104-meter minaret built in 1184 by architect Ahmad Ben Baso. Muezzins once rode horses up these ramps for the call to prayer. At the summit, El Giraldillo—a 4-meter bronze statue representing Faith—has been spinning in the wind since 1568.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "The Royal Alcázar is Europe's oldest inhabited royal palace. In 1364, Peter I summoned Mudéjar craftsmen from Toledo, Granada, and Seville to create this masterpiece in just two years. Step through the doorway of the Patio de las Doncellas: its rectangular pool flanked by marble columns and intricate stucco rivals the Alhambra itself.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "The Alcázar gardens spread across 7 hectares of palms, orange trees, and fountains. The Mercury Pool, the Dance Gardens, and the Grotesque Gallery unfold in welcome coolness. Summer concerts at 'Noches en los Jardines' extend the magic as dusk falls.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Lose yourself in the Barrio de Santa Cruz, the former Jewish quarter where lanes are so narrow two people barely pass. Patios reveal fountains, azulejo tiles, and bougainvillea cascading from wrought-iron balconies. Find your way to Plaza de los Venerables to discover the 17th-century baroque hospice.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The General Archive of the Indies occupies the former Lonja de Mercaderes, a 1598 Renaissance building. Its vaults hold 43,000 files and 80 million pages documenting four centuries of Spanish colonization. The building, cathedral, and Alcázar together form the UNESCO World Heritage site inscribed in 1987.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Catch a flamenco performance at a peña in the historic center. Seville is the birthplace of trianero style, born in the Triana neighborhood across the Guadalquivir.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 75,
