            },
            {
              "text": "Pass through Órgiva (the valley's main town, market day on Thursdays) and climb towards the Barranco de Poqueira, the spectacular gorge where the three most famous villages of the Alpujarras cascade down the mountainside. First stop: Pampaneira (1,058 m), the lower village. Its 340 inhabitants live among whitewashed houses with flat roofs (the \"terraos\"), sloping cobbled lanes, covered passages (the \"tinaos\") and spring-fed fountains. On the main square, taste the water from the San Antonio fountain - legend says it helps you find love. Pampaneira is also the Alpujarras' artisan village: the \"jarapas\", those colorful rugs woven from recycled fibers, are the local specialty. Step into a weaving workshop to watch the artisans at work.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Climb to Bubión (1,296 m), 2 km higher up - on foot via the old mule track (30 minutes) or by car. This is the quietest of the three villages, a member of Spain's \"slow tourism\" network. The Berber architecture is best preserved here: cubic houses with flat slate roofs, cylindrical chimneys topped with a stone cap. At the Museo Casa Alpujarreña, you'll see how the inhabitants lived in the past - kitchen, bedroom and workshop recreated in a traditional house. Don't miss the Artesa de los Moros, a large 2-meter stone whose original purpose remains mysterious.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Capileira (1,436 m) is the highest of the trio, at the gates of Sierra Nevada National Park. From the Mirador de Perchel, the view is vertiginous: to the north, the peak of Veleta (3,396 m); to the south, the rooftops of Bubión and Pampaneira cascading down the valley; and on clear days, the Mediterranean and even the Rif mountains of Morocco on the horizon. This is where the trails begin towards the highest peaks of the Iberian Peninsula, including Mulhacén (3,479 m). The water from the public fountains comes directly from the Sierra Nevada's snowmelt - it's ice-cold even in midsummer.",
