              "text": "Take the road east through the Alpujarras, passing through Pitres and Pórtugos. At Pórtugos, stop at the Fuente Agria - a spring rich in iron that stains the waterfall and surrounding rocks rust-orange. Locals attribute healing properties to it. It's a lovely 20-minute stop in a surprisingly verdant setting for Andalusia.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 20
            },
            {
              "text": "Trevélez is the highest village in mainland Spain, at 1,476 meters altitude, on the slopes of Mulhacén. The village is divided into three neighborhoods (barrios) - bajo, medio and alto - connected by steep cobbled lanes. The barrio bajo is the most touristy, the alto the most authentic. Here, the smell of ham is everywhere: Trevélez is famous throughout Spain for its jamón serrano, naturally cured for 14 to 24 months in drying rooms above 1,200 meters altitude, without any preservatives. The IGP designation \"Jamón de Trevélez\" dates back to 1862, when Queen Isabella II granted the village the privilege of stamping its hams with the royal seal after they won the national competition.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Continue to Válor, 30 minutes east of Trevélez. This discreet village carries a dramatic history: this is where Fernando de Córdoba y Válor was born, who took the Arabic name Abén Humeya claiming descent from the Umayyad caliphs of Córdoba. On Christmas Eve 1568, he led the last great Morisco revolt against Philip II. Within weeks, 25,000 armed men joined him and the insurrection engulfed the entire region. It took the intervention of Don Juan of Austria with 20,000 soldiers to crush the revolt in 1571. More than 80,000 Moriscos were subsequently deported across the peninsula. Every September, Válor reenacts this episode during its Moors and Christians festival.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Visit a ham-drying facility in Trevélez - several producers open their doors to visitors. You'll see hundreds of legs suspended from the ceiling, smell the dry Sierra Nevada air doing the curing work, and taste slices cut right in front of you. The secret of this ham is the altitude: the cold, dry air of the Sierra Nevada, combined with the Mediterranean breeze, creates natural curing conditions that no cold storage facility can replicate.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "1h",
                "tip": "Buy a small vacuum-packed ham as a souvenir - producers also ship by post"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "If you're a hiker, Trevélez is the starting point for climbing Mulhacén (3,479 m), the highest peak of the Iberian Peninsula. The round trip via the Siete Lagunas trail takes 8 to 10 hours and requires good physical condition. For a gentler option, the trail along the río Trevélez through the chestnut groves is family-friendly.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "2h minimum",
                "tip": "For Mulhacén, start at dawn and bring warm clothes - the temperature drops sharply at altitude"
              }
            }
