          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Guadix is one of the most astonishing towns in Andalusia. Founded as Acci by the Iberians, colonized by the Romans (Julius Caesar allegedly founded the colony Julia Gemella Acci here in 45 BC), then governed by the Moors under the name Wadi-Ash, it preserves traces of all these civilizations. But what will strike you is the Barrio de las Cuevas: around 2,000 cave houses still inhabited, spread across 200 hectares - Europe's largest troglodyte settlement. The first caves were dug around 1452 by Moors seeking refuge in the clay hills. Today, 45% of the population lives there, with wifi, heating and fitted kitchens - and a constant temperature of 18-20°C year-round.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Start at the Mirador del Cerro de la Magdalena to take in the full panorama: the white chimneys emerging from the ochre hills, the contrast between the troglodyte quarter and the old town, and the Sierra Nevada as backdrop. Then descend into the cave quarter to walk among whitewashed facades and rainbow-colored doors. Visit the Cueva Museo (Cave Museum), facing the San Miguel church - it recreates life in a cave house with period furniture, and a good explanatory film. If a resident invites you to see their cave (it happens often if you show interest), accept - it's the best way to understand this way of life.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 120
            },
            {
              "text": "In the historic center, the Cathedral of the Incarnation is a surprising monument - built from the 16th to 18th centuries on a former mosque, itself built on an even older temple, it blends Gothic, Renaissance, Baroque and Neoclassical styles. Its red sandstone facade is particularly beautiful in late afternoon light. Right next door, the ruins of the Roman theater, discovered in 2008, date from Emperor Tiberius' reign. The Alcazaba, an 11th-century Arab fortress on the hill, offers the best views of the town and Sierra Nevada - but it's only partially open.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Don't miss the church of Santiago, declared a national monument, with its facade richly sculpted with figures, masks and demons - a striking contrast between the white walls and the reddish-brown ornaments. And if cinema interests you, know that Guadix served as location for \"For a Few Dollars More\" (1965), \"Indiana Jones and the Last Crusade\" and \"Doctor Zhivago\". The lunar landscapes around the town are an open-air studio.",
