              "text": "Baza sits on the Altiplano of Granada, a high plateau at 850 meters altitude whose arid landscapes sometimes evoke Bolivia or New Mexico. The town of 20,000 inhabitants is best known for the Lady of Baza (Dama de Baza), a 4th-century BC Iberian sculpture discovered on July 22, 1971, in the necropolis of Cerro del Santuario. This seated female figure on a throne, originally polychrome (red, blue, white, black), served as a funerary urn - a cavity in her side contained the ashes of a high-ranking woman. The original is in Madrid's National Archaeological Museum, but the local archaeological museum displays a replica and contextualizes the discovery.",
