            {
              "text": "La Seo del Salvador, Zaragoza's oldest cathedral, layers seven centuries of architecture on the site of the ancient Roman forum and later mosque. Its exterior Mudéjar wall, a UNESCO World Heritage site, is a tapestry of brick and glazed ceramics in geometric patterns. Inside, the Gothic polychrome alabaster altarpiece ranks among Europe's finest.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 50
            },
            {
              "text": "The La Seo Tapestry Museum preserves one of the world's finest collections of Flemish tapestries, woven between the 15th and 17th centuries. Biblical and mythological scenes unfold in remarkable condition.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "The Aljafería Palace, built in the 11th century as the \"Palace of Joy\" by King Al-Muqtadir, is the northernmost Islamic palace in Europe. Its polylobed arches, the Patio de Santa Isabel with its orange trees, and the Golden Hall form—together with the Alhambra and Córdoba's Mosque—the triad of Hispano-Muslim architecture.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Cross the Puente de Piedra, a 15th-century stone bridge spanning the Ebro. From the opposite bank, the view of the Basilica del Pilar reflected in the river composes Zaragoza's most iconic image, especially striking at dusk.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 20
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Dive into El Tubo, the labyrinth of narrow downtown alleys dedicated to tapas. Each bar has its specialty: borage in béchamel, Aragonese migas, ternasco lamb. The ritual: one glass of wine and one tapa per counter, then move on.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "The Fountain of Hispanidad, on Plaza del Pilar, represents Latin America in the shape of an inverted map. In the evening, the square comes alive and the illuminated basilica reflects in the fountain's basin.",
