              "visit_duration_min": 40
            },
            {
              "text": "The Cathedral of El Salvador, built in the 16th century on a medieval base, surprises with the austerity of its facade and the richness of its interior. The adjoining Diocesan Museum displays Flemish tapestries, a 14th-century processional cross, and a 16th-century rock crystal fish.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 35
            },
            {
              "text": "Get lost in the sloping alleys climbing toward the castle. The Casa de la Julianeta, crooked and lopsided near the Portal de Molina, has become the village's photographic symbol. The absence of vertical lines in its structure gives it an unreal air, as if lifted from an illustrated storybook.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 25
            },
            {
              "text": "The Plaza Mayor, surrounded by arcaded galleries, is dominated by the 16th-century Town Hall and its fine wooden balconies. From the upper floor, the view plunges onto the Guadalaviar meander that encircles the village like a natural moat.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 20
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Follow the paseo fluvial, a trail along the Guadalaviar, to admire the ramparts from the valley. The contrast between the red sandstone of the walls, the green of the pines, and the blue of the river composes one of Aragon's most photogenic landscapes.",
