            {
              "text": "Castillo de San Gabriel deserves a full hour. Built in the 16th century on a small island to defend against Berber pirates—it was first burned by the corsair Morato in 1586 before being rebuilt in stone—it now houses the Museum of the History of Lanzarote with over 3,000 artifacts. You reach it via the Puente de las Bolas, a drawbridge crowned by two stone cannonballs: this is Arrecife's postcard image. The castle was declared a national historic monument in 1972.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Castillo de San José, perched on the bay of Los Mármoles port, houses the International Museum of Contemporary Art, founded in 1975 on César Manrique's initiative. The building itself dates to the 18th century, and its construction traces back to a legend: in 1630, a French merchant named Francisco García Santaella supposedly founded a hermitage here. The interior blends Baroque, Mudéjar, and Neoclassical styles—a typical Canarian architectural fusion. The castle's panoramic restaurant offers harbor views worth the visit alone.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "End with Calle Real—officially called León y Castillo—Arrecife's main artery for centuries. You'll find the Plazuela (Constitution Square) and San Ginés Church, whose white dome dominates the square where an artisan market sets up every Saturday. The church became a parish in 1798 and was dedicated to San Ginés, the city's patron saint. The complete walk takes 2 to 3 hours.",
