              "text": "Timanfaya National Park is Lanzarote's volcanic heart—and one of Europe's most surreal landscapes. Between September 1, 1730 and April 16, 1736, dozens of volcanoes erupted successively for six years, burying 167 km² of the island, destroying 420 houses, and forcing half the population to emigrate. The 5,107-hectare park was created in 1974 to protect this intact lunar landscape. The visit begins with the Route of the Volcanoes: a 14 km bus circuit through craters, lava tunnels, and red ridges, with multilingual commentary. Arrive early—parking fills fast and the last Route of the Volcanoes entry is at 5 PM.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
