          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Jameos del Agua is César Manrique's first major work in Lanzarote, opened to the public in 1966. The site sits inside a lava tunnel formed by the Corona volcano's eruption about 4,000 years ago—a 6 km tube, 1.5 km of which continues under the ocean (the Atlantis Tunnel, the world's longest underwater cave). You descend through Jameo Chico to an underground saltwater lake, fed by the Atlantic, where blind albino crabs (Munidopsis polymorpha) live—1 cm long and endemic to this place alone. Don't throw coins in the water—rust kills them. The visit continues to Jameo Grande, an open-air cave with a turquoise pool and an auditorium seating 600. Book your ticket online to avoid the line.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Cueva de los Verdes lies minutes from Jameos—it's the same Corona volcanic tube, but here the roof remained intact for nearly a kilometer. The guided tour (mandatory) takes you through geological formations lit by a system designed by Manrique that enhances colors without altering the rock. The cave was used in the 17th century as a refuge by locals fleeing pirates. The visit also hides a visual surprise: prepare for a memorable optical illusion that guides never reveal in advance.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Jardín de Cactus in Guatiza is César Manrique's final major work, inaugurated in 1990—he built it in a former abandoned quarry as a vegetable amphitheater. The garden houses about 4,500 cactus specimens from 500 species originating from five continents, planted on black volcanic stone terraces. The area was historically dedicated to prickly pear cultivation for cochineal dye. At the entrance, an 8-meter cactus sculpture signed by Manrique welcomes you. Allow 45 minutes for the visit.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Detour to the César Manrique Foundation in Tahíche, 20 minutes from Costa Teguise. The artist built his house directly on the 1730 lava flows, integrating five natural volcanic bubbles into the architecture. Since his death in 1992, it's been a museum exhibiting his works and those of international contemporaries. This is where you best understand his philosophy: art and nature must coexist without one crushing the other.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Volcanic malvasía tasting at one of La Geria's vineyards, en route to Costa Teguise. This protected designation of origin produces white wine from grape varieties planted in pits dug into volcanic lapilli, surrounded by semicircular stone walls (zocos) that protect from wind. The landscape is so singular that a photo of La Geria was exhibited in 1964 at New York's MoMA in the \"Architecture Without Architects\" exhibition.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
