          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Santa Cruz de La Palma was founded on May 3, 1493 by Alonso Fernández de Lugo. In the 16th century it became Europe's third port after Antwerp and Seville—riches from the American colonies passed through here. This prosperity left a historic center classified as a Historic-Artistic Ensemble, with 17th and 18th-century palaces and mansions, colorful facades, and carved wooden balconies facing the Atlantic. Start with Avenida Marítima: the 17th-century wooden balconies, flowering and each unique, form one of the Canaries' most photogenic promenades. Note that these enclosed balconies (ajimeces) drew inspiration from Arab architecture and served to cool houses through sea breezes.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Walk up Calle Real—also called Calle O'Daly, named after an Irish banana merchant who lived there. This long cobbled pedestrian street concentrates palaces, craft shops, and small squares. Plaza de España, in the city's heart, is one of the Canaries' finest Renaissance ensembles: the arcaded town hall, public fountain, and El Salvador Church (whose origins date to 1500) form a setting seemingly preserved for five centuries. Casa Salazar, a bit further, is the city's most remarkable Baroque palace—built in the second half of the 17th century, its patio surrounded by wood-balconied galleries is open to the public through temporary exhibitions.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "On the port esplanade, don't miss the Barco de La Virgen—a full-scale replica of Christopher Columbus's Santa María, housing the city's naval museum. Just beside it, Castillo de Santa Catalina, a 16th-century fortification, defended the port against corsair attacks. From the esplanade, the view of the Avenida balconies and the castle facade is Santa Cruz's iconic photo.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Lunch in the historic quarter around Calle Real. La Palma's gastronomy revolves around palmero cheese (PDO), palm honey, and bienmesabe—an almond cream you'll find in every dessert. Pair it with a glass of malvasía wine, produced in the island's vineyards.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "The city is small and entirely walkable in 2 to 3 hours. Late afternoon, climb to Mirador de la Concepción for a panoramic view over the city, colorful balconies, and port. It's the best time of day: the low light ignites the yellow and ochre facades.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Swim in a natural pool on the coast near Santa Cruz, depending on sea conditions. Volcanic pools are numerous on La Palma's east coast—check with your hotel about conditions, as Atlantic swells can be strong.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
