          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Caldera de Taburiente is La Palma's most spectacular national park—protected since 1954, one of Spain's first. This gigantic erosion crater, 8 km in diameter and 1,500 meters deep, is covered with Canarian pine forests and cut by ravines. If you don't wish to hike, Mirador de La Cumbrecita (1,287 m), accessible by car with a permit between 8:30 AM and 4 PM, offers a vertiginous view into the caldera's interior. From up there, the walls rising to over 2,000 m give you the feeling of standing at the bottom of a natural amphitheater.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "For those wanting to enter the caldera on foot, trail PR-LP 13 from Los Brecitos is the most popular (16 km, about 6 hours, -700 m elevation). It descends through Canarian pine forests to the riverbed and passes the Cascada de Colores—a 6-meter waterfall whose rocks are naturally tinted yellow, orange, and red by iron dissolved in the ferrous water of Barranco de las Angustias. The green comes from algae and moss. The spectacle changes with season and flow. Bring plenty of water—there are no services inside.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 360
            },
            {
              "text": "Roque Idafe, a basaltic monolith rising in the caldera's heart, was venerated by the Benahoaritas—La Palma's prehistoric inhabitants—who attributed supernatural powers to it. It stands at the confluence of the Almendro Amargo and Limonero ravines, just before the Cascada de Colores. If you hike here, take a break at this spot: the view of the caldera walls is breathtaking.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
