          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Begin your Madrid stay along the Paseo del Arte, Europe's most concentrated museum triangle. The Prado Museum, founded in 1819 in a neoclassical building by Juan de Villanueva, houses over 8,000 paintings—only a fraction of which are on display. Velázquez's Las Meninas (1656), Hieronymus Bosch's Garden of Earthly Delights (circa 1500), Rubens's The Three Graces, and Goya's Black Paintings await you in the main galleries. Allow at least 2 hours for the major works, longer if you're a painting enthusiast. Arrive at opening time to avoid the queues—they lengthen quickly after 11am.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 150
            },
            {
              "text": "A ten-minute walk south along the Paseo del Prado brings you to the Reina Sofía Museum, housed in the former 18th-century San Carlos Hospital. The museum opened in 1992 and covers Spanish art from 1881 onwards. The absolute star is Picasso's Guernica (1937)—7.76 metres wide, painted in response to the bombing of the Basque village by the German Condor Legion during the Civil War. The room is always crowded, but the canvas is so immense you can see it well from anywhere. Don't miss Dalí's The Great Masturbator and Miró's canvases on the upper floors.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "For a breather between museums, cross the street to Parque del Retiro—125 hectares of greenery right in central Madrid. The park was created in the 17th century as the garden of the Buen Retiro Palace, residence of Philip IV. Rent a rowing boat on the Estanque Grande, facing the Alfonso XII monument, then head to the Crystal Palace (1887), a glass-and-iron greenhouse inspired by London's Crystal Palace, which hosts contemporary art exhibitions from the Reina Sofía. Entry is free.",
