            {
              "text": "Head northeast. After 30 minutes, you reach Atienza, a fortified village clinging to a rocky outcrop at 1,169 m altitude. Seven medieval gates still pierce its ramparts (including the Arco de Arrebatacapas and the Puerta de la Virgen). At the summit, the castle ruins—described by Lonely Planet as seeming like 'a natural extension of the rock'—command a complete panorama over the Guadalajara sierras. Atienza preserves several Romanesque churches, including San Gil (12th century) now converted into a sacred art museum. Plaza del Trigo (Wheat Square), lined with half-timbered houses, is the village heart.",
