              "text": "A thirty-minute drive from Valladolid brings you to Tordesillas, perched on the banks of the Duero. This small town witnessed one of world history's most decisive moments: on June 7, 1494, Spain and Portugal signed the treaty that divided the world between the two crowns, drawing a line 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde Islands. Everything west went to Spain, everything east to Portugal—this treaty explains why Brazil speaks Portuguese today. The Museo del Tratado, housed in the Casas del Tratado, recounts this episode through period documents and maps. The original treaty is listed in UNESCO's Memory of the World Register.",
