              "text": "Long drive from Lerma (2h30 via Burgos and Soria). You leave Duero Castile to enter Guadalajara province. Sigüenza, at nearly 1,000 meters elevation, is one of Spain's best-preserved medieval towns. The cathedral, begun in 1130, combines Romanesque and Gothic. Its massive façade, flanked by two towers, gives it a fortress-like appearance—no accident, as it was built just after the Reconquest. Inside, don't miss the tomb of El Doncel (the page): this funerary sculpture of Martín Vázquez de Arce, who died at 25 in 1486 during the capture of Granada, is considered one of Spanish Gothic's finest. The young man is depicted reclining, reading a book, legs crossed—striking realism for the period.",
