              "text": "The Mezquita-Cathedral of Córdoba is, without exaggeration, one of the most extraordinary monuments on the planet. Begun in 785 by Abd al-Rahman I on the site of a Visigothic basilica, enlarged three times over two centuries, then transformed into a cathedral after the Reconquest of 1236, it layers civilizations within a single 23,400 m² space. Upon entering, you're seized by the forest of more than 850 columns of marble, jasper, and granite—some salvaged from Roman and Visigothic ruins—connected by red-and-white bicolor arches that unfold as far as the eye can see. Push on to Al-Hakam II's mihrab: its golden and blue mosaics, created by artisans sent by the Byzantine emperor, rank among the finest in Islamic art. Then discover the Renaissance cathedral planted in the middle of the mosque—Charles V, who had authorized it, reportedly regretted upon visiting the works: 'You have destroyed what was unique to build what can be seen everywhere.' Arrive at 8:30 AM for free entry (until 9:30 AM)—after that, the queue grows quickly.",
