              "text": "Devote the morning to Medina Azahara (Madinat al-Zahra), the caliphal city that's been a UNESCO site since 2018. Eight kilometers west of Córdoba, at the foot of the Sierra Morena, Abd al-Rahman III ordered in 936 the construction of an entire palatine city to serve as the seat of the Caliphate of Córdoba. Over 75 years, 10,000 workers built a city of 112 hectares on three terraces—royal palaces at the top, gardens and administration in the middle, mosque and dwellings at the bottom. Then, in 1010, the civil war that ended the caliphate reduced it to ashes. It remained buried for a millennium, until its rediscovery in 1910. Today, only 10% has been excavated, but the Salón Rico (official reception hall), with its arches and carved stone panels of insane delicacy, conveys the measure of what this 'Andalusian Versailles' once was. The museum at the base of the site is excellent—start there to understand what you're about to see. Allow at least 2.5 hours.",
