          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Salamanca's Plaza Mayor is often called Spain's most beautiful square—and once you see it, you'll understand why. Commissioned by Philip V in 1710, built from 1729 by Alberto de Churriguera and completed only in 1755, it's a masterpiece of Spanish Baroque framed by two-story arcades. Look for the sculpted medallions on the arches: you'll find kings, conquistadors, and even Franco—though he's since been removed following historical memory legislation. At the corner location, Café Novelty has been serving since 1905; it's the perfect spot for a break with a view. Arrive early morning or after 8pm for local atmosphere, as school groups flood the square during the day.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Salamanca's twin cathedrals are joined together and visited as one. The Catedral Vieja, begun around 1150 in Romanesque style, houses one of Spain's most complete collections of medieval altarpieces—53 painted panels from the 15th century. The Catedral Nueva, built between the 16th and 18th centuries in late Gothic style, is notably more imposing. On the north facade, restored in 1992, look for an astronaut and a demon eating ice cream—added according to the tradition that each restoration should include a contemporary figure. You enter the old cathedral through the new one, with a single combined ticket.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "The facade of Salamanca's University, founded in 1218 by Alfonso IX of León—one of Europe's oldest—is covered with plateresque carvings so dense they're sometimes compared to stone lace. The classic game: find the hidden frog on the facade. Legend says whoever finds it will pass their exams. The interior, notably the old lecture hall called Aula de Fray Luis de León, is open for visits and worth the stop.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The Casa de las Conchas is a 15th-century Gothic civil palace whose facade is covered with over 350 stone scallop shells—the emblem of the Order of Santiago to which its owner, Rodrigo Arias Maldonado, belonged. Now a public library, entry is free and the interior courtyard is worth five minutes of your time.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Late in the day, walk down to the Puente Romano and the riverbank viewpoint along the Tormes to watch the silhouette of both cathedrals at sunset. It's the best photo angle in Salamanca. From the Roman bridge—26 arches, built under Trajan, the city's only access point for two thousand years—the orange light on Villamayor stone is the spectacle that earned the city its nickname 'La Dorada' (the Golden One).",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
