              "Vega Terrón Miranda do Douro"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "The Arribes del Duero Natural Park stretches for nearly 100 kilometers of canyons carved by the Duero River through granite, forming the natural border between Spain and Portugal. The cliffs plunge up to 500 meters—the deepest gorges in the entire Iberian Peninsula. The Mirador del Fraile, at Aldeadávila de la Ribera, offers the most vertiginous viewpoint: a walkway overhangs the canyon directly, not recommended if you have a fear of heights. From there, the Duero's waters seem motionless, they're so far below. Bring water as the trails are exposed.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Pozo de los Humos is one of the peninsula's most spectacular waterfalls: the Uces River plunges into the canyon from over 50 meters, creating a permanent cloud of spray that gave it its name ('well of smoke'). The trail from Masueco is short (2.3 km round trip) and accessible to all, but stones are slippery in wet season. In summer, flow can be low depending on the year's rainfall—choose spring or autumn to see the falls at full force.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Make a detour through Fermoselle, a town declared a historic and artistic site, perched on the heights with views over the confluence of the Duero and Esla. The town is nicknamed 'the town of a thousand cellars'—caves carved into the rock beneath houses to store wine from the Arribes terroir, a developing denomination of origin with eleven vineyards planted on terraces. The viewpoints at the castle and Las Escaleras are worth the stop.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Walk sections of the GR-14, the long-distance trail that follows the Duero from its source to Porto. In the Arribes sector, several sections above the gorges are accessible in 1 to 3 hours. The microclimate warmer than the rest of Castile—due to the deep gorges trapping heat—allows olive trees, almonds and vines to grow at this latitude. Look up: golden eagles, griffon vultures and black storks nest on the rock walls.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
              "practical_info": {
                "distance": "variable by section",
                "duration": "1h to 3h",
                "difficulty": "Easy to moderate"
              }
            }
