              "Iglesia de La Magdalena Zamora",
              "Iglesia Santiago de los Caballeros Zamora",
              "Mirador del Troncoso Zamora",
              "Puente de Piedra Zamora"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Zamora's cathedral is nicknamed 'The Pearl of the Duero'—and once you see its scaled stone dome, you'll understand why. Built between 1151 and 1174, consecrated in 1175, it's the oldest cathedral in Castile and León. Its cimborrio (lantern tower) with sixteen double arches showing Byzantine, Islamic and French Romanesque influences is a unique creation in Spanish Romanesque art. Inside, don't miss the Cathedral Museum which houses one of the world's finest collections of 15th-century Flemish tapestries, from the workshops of Arras, Tournai and Brussels. Check opening times before coming, as the cathedral closes during certain exhibition periods.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Zamora has over twenty Romanesque churches in the old town—making it the densest concentration in Europe according to several art historians. Follow the Romanesque circuit from Plaza de Viriato: the church of La Magdalena, with its carved doorway and oriental sepulcher, then Santiago de los Caballeros, where tradition places El Cid's knighting by Ferdinand I. The Mirador del Troncoso, at the end of the ramparts, gives panoramic views over the Duero and the plains of Castile.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Zamora's ramparts extend over a kilometer along the rocky promontory overlooking the Duero. Built in several phases from the 9th century onward, they're among the best preserved in Spain. Look for the Portillo de la Traición—a small gate in the wall through which, according to legend, the assassin of King Sancho II was introduced during the siege of Zamora in 1072. This is the origin of the Spanish proverb 'Zamora wasn't taken in an hour.'",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Late afternoon, head down to Playa de Los Pelambres on the Duero's banks to view the silhouette of the cathedral and castle from the opposite shore. The medieval stone bridge, crossing point of the Via de la Plata—the Roman road that linked Mérida to Astorga—holds one of Spain's oldest sets of aceñas (water mills). This is the best angle for photographing the historic ensemble.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
