              "Cueva de La Cuevona Las Médulas"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Las Médulas is Castile and León's strangest landscape: reddish sand pinnacles rise from a forest of oaks and chestnuts, like a fantasy film set. This isn't natural geology—it's the direct result of the Roman Empire's largest open-pit gold mine. The Romans extracted approximately 800,000 kilos of gold here between the 1st and 3rd centuries, using a process called 'ruina montium': they stored colossal amounts of water in mountain basins, then released it all at once to explode the rock. Over 400 km of canals and aqueducts were built to feed this system. Listed as UNESCO in 1997, the site has remained intact since the mines were abandoned. Start at the Interpretation Center in the village to understand the operation's scale before heading out on the trails.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Climb up to the Mirador de Orellán for the overview of the site—from here the spectacle is most striking: the jagged red formations stand out against the green forests, with the Aquilanos mountains in the background. The sunset from this viewpoint is one of the most photographed in León province. Allow 30 minutes uphill from the Orellán parking lot.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Walk the Senda de las Valiñas, a circular route from Las Médulas village that penetrates the heart of the mining site. The trail crosses the open-air galleries, skirts Lake Carucedo (formed by stagnant water accumulation during Roman works) and passes through the caves of La Cuevona and La Encantada—galleries hand-dug for the hydraulic system. Easy, marked, about 2 hours. If you have more time, the Peripheral Trail (4h) makes the complete circuit and includes the ruins of the Orellán settlement.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
