            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "To reach Peñalba de Santiago, you must cross the entire Valley of Silence by a single-lane road once called 'the monks' path.' Perched at 1,100 meters in the Aquilanos mountains, this village of about fifty inhabitants is one of Spain's most beautiful: stone and slate houses with wooden balconies, lanes so narrow they seem never to have changed since the 10th century. Park at the entrance lot—the lanes are impassable by car.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The Mozarabic church of Santiago de Peñalba is the only remnant of the monastery founded by San Genadio in the 10th century, completed in 937 by Abbot Salomón. It's a jewel of Spanish Mozarabic architecture—a style born from the fusion of Visigothic traditions and Arab influences. Enter through the double door with horseshoe arches supported by three marble columns: inside, the horseshoe arches divide the nave, and remnants of medieval wall paintings survive on the walls. This is where the body of San Genadio rests.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "From the village, a half-hour walk on the old monks' path leads to the Cave of San Genadio, carved into a vertical rock face at the very entrance to the Valley of Silence. The Bishop of Astorga retreated here to meditate in the 9th century. A local legend says he ordered the Oza River to be silent so as not to disturb his prayer—and the river disappeared underground at that spot.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "The Valley of Silence is also a beautiful invitation to hike in a landscape of oak, chestnut and walnut forests crossed by the Oza River. The trail climbing to the Monastery of San Pedro de Montes (founded in the 7th century by San Fructuoso, rebuilt in the 12th-13th centuries) is one of the region's most beautiful. Allow 3 hours round trip from Peñalba.",
