            "map_keywords": [
              "Palacio Episcopal Gaudí Astorga",
              "Catedral de Astorga",
              "Murallas Romanas Astorga",
              "Museo Romano Astorga",
              "Plaza Mayor Astorga",
              "Castrillo de los Polvazares Astorga"
            ]
          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "The Episcopal Palace of Astorga is one of Gaudí's few works outside Catalonia—and it's as surprising as any of his Barcelona buildings. After the old palace burned down in 1886, Bishop Joan Grau i Vallespinós, originally from Catalonia and Gaudí's childhood friend, commissioned him to build the new one. From 1887, Gaudí designed a neo-Gothic edifice in white granite combining the forms of a castle, temple and manor house. The moat, battlements, four circular towers and multicolored stained glass windows—inspired by León Cathedral—bear his signature. Bishop Grau's death in 1893 prompted Gaudí to abandon the site, with the top floor completed without him by architect Ricardo García Guereta. Today the palace houses the Museum of the Ways of Saint James. Book tickets online; audio guides are available in English.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "Astorga Cathedral adjoins Gaudí's palace, forming a striking ensemble. Begun in 1471 on the site of an earlier Romanesque cathedral, it blends Gothic, Renaissance and Baroque according to the centuries of construction. Its Baroque facade is particularly ornate. On an apse pinnacle, spot the statue of Pedro Mato, a legendary figure of the Maragatería whose identity remains mysterious. Inside, the main altarpiece and carved choir are worth stopping for.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Astorga is a Roman town founded under Augustus as Asturica Augusta, and the remains are remarkably well preserved. The Roman Museum, accessed through the Ergastula (2nd-century Roman dungeon still standing), displays discoveries from local excavations. The baths, forum and Domus of the Bear and Birds—with its Roman mosaics in place—complete the visit. The city was the hub of several major Roman roads, including the one linking Bordeaux to Astorga. This crossroads also explains its role as an essential stop on the Way of St. James.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Five kilometers from Astorga, the village of Castrillo de los Polvazares is the best-preserved example of Maragato architecture—reddish stone houses aligned on a single paved street, carriage gates, absolute silence. The Maragatería is a unique region whose inhabitants, the Maragatos, had a reputation as muleteer-transporters of goods between Galicia and Castile. Their traditional dish, cocido maragato, is served backwards from other Spanish cocidos: meat first, broth last.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
