          },
          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Orbaneja del Castillo is perhaps Spain's most improbable village: a 25-meter waterfall emerges directly from the Cueva del Agua, flows through the village dividing houses into two quarters, and plunges into the Ebro below. Along the way, the water has formed terraced pools with turquoise reflections surrounded by green moss—the contrast is striking. The village, declared a historic site in 1993, has about fifty inhabitants and stone lanes where time seems frozen. Park at the lot outside the center.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Cueva del Agua, from which the waterfall springs, is a karst cave you can visit guided in summer and on weekends. From the upper part of the town, climb to Orbaneja's natural viewpoint for a plunging view over the Ebro canyon—the limestone walls cut out rock silhouettes that locals compare to African profiles. Also look for the natural arch that the river has sculpted in the cliff above the village.",
