              "text": "San Felices de los Gallegos encapsulates the turbulent history of the Spanish-Portuguese frontier. The castle was built in 1296 by King Denis I of Portugal, who had just occupied the town. The annexation by Portugal was confirmed in 1297 at the Treaty of Alcañices. In 1326, San Felices returned to Castilian control as a royal marriage dowry. But that was far from the end of sovereignty exchanges: the town was retaken by the Portuguese during the Castilian War of Succession in the 15th century, then pillaged again during the Portuguese Restoration War in 1646. Its castle is the best-preserved of the four in Arribes del Duero Natural Park.",
