          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Start the day at the Monastery of Yuste, a European Heritage site nestled in the Sierra de Gredos foothills near Cuacos de Yuste. This is where Charles V—Charles I of Spain and V of the Holy Roman Empire, the most powerful man in the world—chose to retire after abdicating in 1556 in favor of his son Philip II. He arrived on February 3, 1557, with an entourage of about sixty people. His chamber was positioned against the church choir so he could attend mass from his bed—he suffered from terrible gout that confined him to his litter. He died here on September 21, 1558, at age 58, from malarial fevers. The visit shows both cloisters (one Gothic, one Renaissance), the 15th-century church, and the emperor's apartments—surprisingly austere for the man who'd ruled an empire where the sun never set.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "Head to Coria in the afternoon (50 km, 45 minutes). This town is one of Spain's oldest—the ancient Caurium of the Vettones, which became a Roman municipium. Its Roman walls, built between the 3rd and 4th centuries, are probably the best-preserved as a whole set in all of Europe: over 1,100 meters of ramparts with about twenty square towers and four gates, two of them original Roman (Puerta del Sol and Puerta de la Guía). The walls are 8 meters thick in places. Walk the circuit—it's about a 30-minute stroll that gives you vertigo when you think these stones have been standing for 1,700 years.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Coria's cathedral, built between the 15th and 18th centuries on the remains of a Visigothic church, blends Gothic, Plateresque, and Baroque styles. Its Plateresque facade is remarkable, as is its Churrigueresque tower offering superb views over town and countryside. The cathedral guards an extraordinary relic: what's claimed to be the tablecloth from Christ's Last Supper, attested in a papal bull from 1404. Admission is free and opening hours are generous (closed Monday mornings).",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 40
            },
            {
              "text": "Don't miss the bridge without a river—Coria's most surreal image. This five-arched stone bridge, built in the 16th century probably on earlier Roman foundations, spanned the Río Alagón. But the river changed course—likely gradually following floods, worsened by the 1755 Lisbon earthquake—and now flows several hundred meters away. Result: a bridge without a river and a river without a bridge. Walk under the arches for the best photo, especially late afternoon.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 20
            },
            {
              "text": "If daylight permits, detour 30 minutes to Granadilla, a fascinating ghost village. This fortified villa of Almohad origin (9th century), which governed 15 municipalities under its jurisdiction in the Middle Ages, was emptied of inhabitants in 1955 when Franco's regime decided to build the Gabriel y Galán dam. Cruel irony: the water never reached the village. Declared a Conjunto Histórico-Artístico in 1980, it was partially restored through an educational program. You can visit the cobbled lanes, the circular wall (one of Spain's best-preserved alongside Lugo and Ávila), and the 15th-century castle built by the Duke of Alba, whose terrace offers striking views over the reservoir and hills.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "In the evening in Coria, try dulces de las monjas—cloistered convent sweets. The town's convents sell handmade pastries (quemados, dulces de yema) through a rotating hatch, without seeing the nuns who make them. It's a typically Spanish tradition that persists in Extremadura's small towns.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 30,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "30min",
                "tip": "The convent is near the Plaza Mayor. Ring the bell and wait—the nuns aren't in a hurry"
              }
            }
          ],
