          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Zafra is nicknamed \"little Seville\" for its white streets, flower-filled patios, and Andalusian atmosphere—but it's stayed far quieter than its big neighbor. Start with the Alcázar de los Duques de Feria, a 15th-century fortress flanked by nine crenellated towers, now converted to a Parador. Hernán Cortés stayed here before sailing off to conquer Mexico. Even if you're not spending the night, step inside to see the arcaded interior courtyard and coffered ceilings—Parador staff are used to curious visitors.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 40
            },
            {
              "text": "Zafra has two adjoining squares forming the town's heart. Plaza Grande, vast and airy, is lined with porticoes sheltering cafés and terraces. Plaza Chica, more intimate, was the medieval market site—the stone columns bordering it still bear the marks of standard measures carved by merchants to verify weights and lengths. The covered passage connecting the two squares is a charming detail.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "The Colegiata de la Candelaria, from the 15th century, is Zafra's main church. Its main altarpiece is impressive and its position on Plaza Grande makes it a natural landmark. Just next door, the Convento de Santa Clara (15th century) shelters remarkable altarpieces and wrought-iron grilles.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Enter Zafra through the Puerta de Jerez, one of Extremadura's finest town gates. From there, wander the historic center's streets, declared a Bien de Interés Cultural—the whitewashed palaces, wrought-iron balconies, and patios glimpsed through half-open doors justify the town's nickname. In the evening, the atmosphere on Plaza Grande's terraces is delightful.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Zafra sits at the heart of Tierra de Barros, Extremadura's main wine region. Tour operators offer bodega visits in the area, especially toward Almendralejo (30 km), the region's \"wine capital.\" Extremadura wines, long underrated, have improved tremendously—try reds from tempranillo and garnacha, and whites from pardina and cayetana.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "2h",
                "tip": "Booking recommended for bodega visits. Almendralejo is 20 minutes from Zafra"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "If you prefer staying in town, Zafra hosts a lively flea market on Thursdays in Plaza Grande, a direct legacy of the medieval fairs that made the town prosperous. The Feria Internacional Ganadera (livestock fair) in September–October is one of Lower Extremadura's major events—if you're there then, don't miss it.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "1h",
                "tip": "Thursday is the best day to visit Zafra—market plus old town animation"
              }
            }
