          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Dedicate the day to Olivenza, 85 km northwest of Zafra. It's one of Spain's most unusual places: a Portuguese town on Spanish soil. Founded by the Templars in the 13th century, it remained Portuguese for five centuries (1297–1801) before being annexed by Spain during the brief War of the Oranges. Portugal has never recognized this annexation—officially, Olivenza is still claimed by Lisbon. Result: black-and-white Portuguese-style cobblestones, Manueline architecture, and azulejos coexist with Spanish signage. Since 2010, street names are posted in both languages.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "The Igreja de Santa María Magdalena is Olivenza's masterpiece and the finest example of Manueline architecture outside Portugal—after Lisbon's Jerónimos Monastery. Commissioned by King Manuel I in 1510 and completed in 1560, it has three naves resting on eight twisted granite columns typical of Manueline style. The walls are covered with 18th-century blue-and-white azulejos, and six baroque altarpieces complete the ensemble. In 2012, Spanish internet users voted it \"Spain's most beautiful corner\"—a delicious paradox for an utterly Portuguese monument.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Olivenza's castle, built by the Templars then reinforced under Portuguese kings, has a keep tower 37 meters high—the tallest on the entire Spanish-Portuguese border. Erected in 1488 on flat terrain, it had to compensate through height what the land didn't provide in natural defense. It's accessed by a ramp (no stairs)—so it's accessible to all. From the top, the panorama sweeps across the plain to the Guadiana and Portugal. The castle also houses the Museo Etnográfico González Santana, one of Extremadura's richest ethnographic museums.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Stop by the Santa Casa de la Misericordia, founded in 1501 by King Manuel I himself. The chapel's interior walls are covered with 18th-century Portuguese azulejos depicting Old and New Testament scenes—a remarkable collection. The town hall on Plaza de la Constitución preserves a Manueline doorway that's the town symbol.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Olivenza is a gastronomic border post: you'll eat migas extremeñas alongside bacalhau Portuguese-style, and convent pastries blend traditions from both countries. Lunch in the historic center and taste both cuisines—it's the only place in Spain where that's possible in the same village.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 90,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "1h30",
                "tip": "Olivenza is 85 km from Zafra (1h10 drive). Plan the whole day"
              }
            }
          ],
