          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Jerez de los Caballeros is the final stop on this itinerary—and what a finale. Birthplace of Vasco Núñez de Balboa, the first European to sight the Pacific Ocean in 1513, it has a spectacular historic center dominated by the silhouettes of its baroque towers. The Templar fortress, built in the 13th century when the Knights Templar controlled this frontier with Muslim Andalusia, overlooks the town from a hilltop. It's in the Torre Sangrienta (Bloody Tower) that Jerez's last Templars were supposedly massacred in 1312 during the dissolution of the order. The legend is probably exaggerated, but it fits the mood of the place.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Jerez's two baroque churches are among Extremadura's finest. The Iglesia de San Bartolomé has a bell tower covered in colorful azulejos that recalls Seville's bell towers—it's the town's iconic image. The Iglesia de La Encarnación, with its own slender baroque tower, completes an urban landscape you'd swear was Andalusian. Climb the sloping streets to discover the noble palaces, carved coats of arms, and flower-filled patios that built the reputation of this conquistador town.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 40
            },
            {
              "text": "On Plaza de Vasco Núñez de Balboa, a statue honors the town's most famous son. Born here around 1475, Balboa sailed for the New World in 1500 and crossed the Isthmus of Panama in 1513 to become the first European to see the Pacific Ocean. The plaza also offers fine views over the surrounding hills covered in holm oaks—the dehesa landscape that characterizes all of Lower Extremadura.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 20
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Jerez de los Caballeros sits at the heart of the jamón ibérico de bellota production zone—the world's finest ham. Black Iberian pigs roam free in the dehesas, feeding on holm oak acorns during the montanera (autumn). If you're passing October through February, you'll see the pigs under the oaks—a unique landscape. Regional tour operators offer visits to ham-curing facilities with tastings. Even out of season, every bar in Jerez serves hand-sliced jamón ibérico—it's the best way to close this Extremadura journey.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 90,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "1h30",
                "tip": "Ask for jamón ibérico de bellota—not just 'ibérico.' The taste difference is immense"
              }
            }
          ]
