              "text": "Ourense is Galicia's 'thermal capital'—and thermal waters have been the very reason for its existence for 2,000 years. Start at As Burgas, right in the historic centre: two monumental fountains (the 17th-century Burga de Arriba and the 19th-century Burga de Abaixo) from which water gushes out at 67°C. The Romans built baths here and worshipped the 'nymphs of the springs.' Local legend claims the springs originate beneath the Santo Cristo chapel inside the cathedral. You can touch the water (careful—it's scalding) and even drink it, though its sulphurous taste isn't particularly pleasant; its curative properties, however, are well documented. The modern, free-entry As Burgas Interpretation Centre explains the geology and history of the site.",
