          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Welcome to Segovia. The city reveals itself from afar by its silhouette—some say it resembles a ship. The Alcázar as bow, the cathedral as mainmast, the aqueduct as anchor cast into the sierra. The Roman aqueduct is your arrival point: 167 arches, 28 meters high at its peak, granite assembled without mortar—not a drop of cement across the 800 visible meters. Built around 50 CE, more likely under Domitian than Trajan. For the best photo, climb the Postigo stairs on the right: you'll find yourself level with the water channel, and it's from there you grasp the brilliant absurdity of this engineering feat.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Alcázar, perched at the tip of the promontory, genuinely inspired Walt Disney for Snow White's castle—he visited in 1935. Built from the 11th century on former Roman fortifications, expanded in the 13th by Castilian kings, ravaged by fire in 1862 and rebuilt immediately afterward in fairy-tale fashion. Inside you'll find the throne room, the chamber of the Catholic Monarchs where Isabella was proclaimed queen in 1474, and—warning to the truly brave—152 spiral steps up the Torre de Juan II. The view plunges toward the Sierra de Guadarrama and the convents of the Eresma valley.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "The cathedral, nicknamed \"the Lady of Cathedrals\" for its elegance, is the last Gothic cathedral built in Spain—construction began in 1525 under Charles V after the previous one burned during the Comuneros revolt in 1520. Latin cross plan, 18 chapels, spectacular 16th-century Flemish stained glass. In the Concepción chapel, Ignacio de Ries's Tree of Life is a macabre curiosity: a giant crucifix as tree root, the damned falling to hell from the lower branches. Far from joyful.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Church of Vera Cruz, 10 minutes downhill from the Alcázar (then plan for the climb back), is one of the city's best-kept secrets. Dodecagonal plan—twelve sides—built by the Templars in 1208 and consecrated April 13 of that year by papal decree of Innocent III. At its center, a two-story shrine where knights kept vigil over a relic of the True Cross. It's rare in Europe, and that's what makes it remarkable: Vera Cruz has barely changed since the 13th century. Further on, the Parral monastery is under permanent restoration but accessible.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
