          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "At 1,131 meters altitude, Ávila is one of Spain's highest cities—and you feel it in winter, when it often snows. The city reveals itself first through its ramparts: 2.5 kilometers of intact wall, 88 semi-circular towers, 9 monumental gates. Built from 1080 on orders of Raymond of Burgundy, son-in-law of Alfonso VI of Castile-León, completed in 1101. It's the best-preserved medieval wall in Europe—it nearly got demolished in the 19th century when authorities judged it stifled urban expansion. Fortunately they gave up. The walkway runs 1,700 meters.",
