              "text": "On the wall itself, the Cathedral del Salvador. It gave birth to the term \"fortress-cathedral\" in architectural vocabulary. Its apse, nicknamed the Cimorro, literally forms part of the defensive system—it's one of the rampart towers, pierced with arrow slits. Spain's first Gothic cathedral, begun around 1170 by master Fruchel, a Burgundian architect influenced by Saint-Denis. Built in oxblood sandstone that gives it its unique color. Inside, the main altarpiece by Pedro Berruguete and Juan de Borgoña, the tomb of El Tostado (the bishop-writer who published 50 volumes in 25 years, died 1455).",
              "place_id": "",
