              "text": "Ávila makes no sense without Teresa. Born here in 1515 to a family of converted Jewish merchants, she reformed the Carmelite order, founded 17 monasteries, wrote The Interior Castle, and became the first female Doctor of the Church in 1970. Her birthplace was transformed in the 17th century into a convent and baroque basilica. The adjoining museum displays some strange relics: a finger of the saint preserved in a monstrance, her cane, autograph manuscripts. More moving: the Monastery of the Incarnation, outside the walls, where she lived 27 years and experienced the famous \"transverberation\" (vision where a seraph pierces her heart).",
