          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Salamanca's Plaza Mayor is considered Spain's most beautiful baroque square—and it's hard to argue. Commissioned in 1729 by Philip V in gratitude to the city for its support in the War of Succession, designed by Alberto de Churriguera, completed in 1755. 88 arcades on three sides, the fourth occupied by the town hall. Look for the stone medallions in the spandrels: Christopher Columbus, Cervantes, Cortés, Franco (yes, removed and restored depending on the era). The local sandstone turns orange at sunset—hence the nickname \"golden city.\"",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The University of Salamanca, founded in 1218 by Alfonso IX of León, is Spain's oldest university and Europe's fourth oldest (after Bologna, Paris, Oxford). Christopher Columbus defended his project here in 1486; Antonio de Nebrija published the first Spanish grammar here in 1492. The Plateresque façade of the Escuelas Mayores (1529) is so finely carved it resembles stone goldsmithing. The challenge: find the lucky frog on one of the three skulls in the pediment. Students say you'll pass your exams if you spot it alone. Hint: on the right, on the rightmost skull. Tell no one.",
