              "text": "The Roman Bridge—Puente Mayor del Tormes—dates from the 1st century CE and was part of the Vía de la Plata, the Roman road linking Mérida to Astorga. The southern half was rebuilt in the 17th century after a flood. At the bridge's end, a pre-Roman sculpture—perhaps a Vettonian verraco, perhaps an Iberian bull—over 2,000 years old. The bridge is pedestrian, perfect for photographing both cathedrals from the other bank. Lazarillo de Tormes, Spain's first picaresque novel (1554), begins precisely when Lazarillo's master forces him to ram his head against this stone.",
