          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Tarragona's Roman amphitheatre is arguably Spain's most photogenic - not the largest (14,000 seats versus the Colosseum's 50,000), but the only one built facing the sea, with waves crashing just 30 meters behind the arena. Constructed around 120 AD under Hadrian, it witnessed the martyrdom of Bishop Fructuosus, burned alive in 259 during the Christian persecutions in Hispania. At the center stand the foundations of a 6th-century Visigothic basilica built directly over the arena floor. Allow 45 minutes; admission is part of the combined Tarraco ticket (€15, covering 4 sites).",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Passeig Arqueològic follows Tarraco's cyclopean ramparts for 1,100 meters, shaded by cypress and olive trees. Built in the 2nd century BC by Romans who arrived in Hispania in 218 BC during the Second Punic War, these walls rank among the oldest surviving Roman structures outside Italy. The Archbishop's Tower and Minerva Tower (the latter bearing a Latin inscription from the 2nd century BC, among the oldest on the peninsula) punctuate the route. This shaded promenade is ideal for early morning. Allow 1 hour; closed Mondays.",
