          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "The Seu Vella crowns the hill that defines Lleida's skyline—you can make it out from the Pyrenees on clear days. Begun in 1203 by Pere de Coma on the remains of a mosque, consecrated in 1278, and completed in 1431 with its bell tower—more than two centuries of construction. It's considered Europe's last great Romanesque cathedral, already showing Gothic elements. Then in 1707, Philip V closed it for worship and turned it into a military barracks for 240 years. Now restored to heritage status, it opens for visits including its giant cloister—one of Europe's largest—and the Gothic bell tower. 238 spiral steps for the view.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 105
            },
            {
              "text": "Atop the Turó, just above the cathedral, the Castell del Rei—la Suda—overlooks what remains of a Muslim castle documented since 882. Palace of the kings of Aragon from the 12th to 16th centuries, destroyed during the 18th-century wars and finished off by an explosion during the Napoleonic wars. Less than a quarter survives, but the interpretation center housed in the royal hall tells the story of how Lleida shifted from al-Andalus to the Crown of Aragon. A hillside elevator makes the site accessible to those with reduced mobility—rare for this type of monument.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Below, the Catedral Nova on Carrer Major was built between the 18th and 19th centuries to replace the confiscated Seu Vella. Neoclassical style, more sober façade. Inside, the Virgin of Blau bears a mark on her forehead: legend says a sculptor jealous of his apprentice's work tried to smash the statue with a hammer; the hammer bounced back and killed him, leaving the Virgin with that bluish bruise that gives her name. The first name Blau, still common in Lleida, comes from this.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The Palau de la Paeria, on the plaza of the same name, serves as Lleida's town hall—and ranks among Catalonia's finest Gothic civic buildings. Built in the early 13th century by the lords of Sanaüja, donated to the city in 1383 to serve as municipal headquarters, the building has two façades: civil Romanesque facing the plaza, neoclassical facing the Segre. The archives preserve the Charta del Poble, one of the earliest known urban constitutions, dated to the 12th century. Free weekday visits.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "One last detour before the break: the Dipòsit del Pla de l'Aigua, nicknamed the \"water cathedral.\" Built in the late 18th century, it's simply the city's first drinking water reservoir—25 stone pillars, 6 barrel vaults, 9-million-liter capacity. Closed then forgotten for decades, it now opens for visits. Don't miss the acoustics: clap beneath the vault, the sound returns eight times.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
