          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "On the road from Lleida, stop at Coll de Nargó. The village harbors the Romanesque church of Sant Climent, but especially its paleontological site: one of Europe's most important dinosaur egg deposits, 70 million years old. The Dinosfera center lets you see fossilized nests in situ and reconstructs the late Cretaceous ecosystem. Curious fact: Ramon Lambard, the architect who completed La Seu d'Urgell's cathedral, also came from Coll de Nargó. Count on an hour on site.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Arguably the masterpiece of Catalan Romanesque art: the Cathedral of Santa Maria d'Urgell, the only entirely Romanesque cathedral surviving in the region. Construction launched in 1116 by Bishop Saint Ot, completed in 1183 under Ramon Lambard. Basilica plan with three naves, transept with five apses, and especially that Italian gallery above the façade—a detail found nowhere else in Catalonia. The very thick walls hide another truth: the cathedral also served as a fortress, which is why it has lasted eight centuries. The central portal concentrates all the sculptural decoration.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "The adjoining cloister is slightly trapezoidal in plan, an oddity you notice from the entrance. Three 12th-century Romanesque galleries with historiated capitals—vegetal motifs, human figures, monsters; the fourth was redone in the 17th century. It serves as passage to the church of Sant Miquel and the diocesan museum. The museum is worth the detour for one piece alone: the Beatus of La Seu d'Urgell, an illuminated Mozarabic manuscript of the Commentary on the Apocalypse, early 10th century. One of the oldest preserved in the world.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "The Carrer dels Canonges, the old town's main street, runs along the former defensive moats filled in during the 16th century. Seigneurial houses in a row: Cal Tarragona, Cal Calçot, Cal Patalín. Originally, this was the street of the cathedral canons. Today, cheese shops (La Seu d'Urgell is Catalonia's cheese capital), artisan boutiques, terrace cafés. The Tower of Solsona, isolated from the rest of Castellciutat's walls, is a 5-minute walk above town and offers the best view of the cathedral.",
