          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "On the road from La Seu d'Urgell, stop at the Congost de Collegats—spectacular gorges carved by the Noguera Pallaresa between 500-meter limestone walls. Now bypassed by a tunnel, the old road still winds along the bottom of the defile: drive slowly, stop at the viewpoints. This is where Gaudí supposedly found inspiration for the undulating columns of the Sagrada Família, seeing the rock called \"L'Argenteria.\" True or false, the landscape fully justifies the stop.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "A little treasure 8 km south of Sort: Gerri de la Sal, medieval village enclosed within its 14th-century ramparts. Rock salt was exploited here since Roman times—hence the name. The monastery of Santa Maria, founded in 807, is one of Catalonia's oldest. And just beside it, the old salt warehouses (Alfolí) overlook the Noguera. It's typical of these Pyrenean villages, both rough and refined. Count 45 minutes to walk around.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Sort, capital of Pallars Sobirà, doesn't look like much at first glance—classic mountain village, stone houses and slate roofs. But it's the epicenter of whitewater sports in Spain, since the 1980s. This is where rafting was introduced to the country. The name Sort means \"luck\" in Catalan, and the municipality is famous for its lottery office: La Bruixa d'Or—the golden witch—sells winning tickets all across Spain, people come expressly to buy their ticket. Touristy, but it's become an institution.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "If you have time in late afternoon, push on to Esterri d'Àneu, 30 km up the valley toward Bonaigua. The Ecomuseu des Valls d'Àneu reconstructs early 20th-century Pyrenean herders' life in period buildings: restored Casa Gassia, stable, barn, bread oven. The Valls d'Àneu still maintain active transhumance today. For Romanesque art enthusiasts, take advantage to see the church of Sant Just i Pastor de Son, 5 km away.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            }
