          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "First of all, stop at the Centre del Romànic in Erill la Vall to understand what you're about to see. Small museum—30 minutes suffices—that places the valley's nine churches in context: Lombard masters from northern Italy in the 12th century, fresco al fresco technique, Erill sculptural school, rediscovery by Puig i Cadafalch in 1907 during an expedition by the Institute of Catalan Studies. The combined ticket gives access to several valley churches—economical if you plan to see three or four.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The journey's highlight: Sant Climent de Taüll. Consecrated December 10, 1123 by the Bishop of Roda, it's the valley's best-preserved Romanesque building. Basilica plan with three naves, three apses, and especially that six-story square bell tower—characteristic Lombard decoration with its arcatures and saw-tooth friezes. Inside, the original apse was decorated with a masterful fresco of Christ Pantocrator, removed by strappo in 1919 and preserved at the MNAC in Barcelona. On site, a video-mapping projection reconstructs the original frescoes on the walls: technically spectacular, and more moving than you'd think.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "200 meters uphill in the village, Santa Maria de Taüll—consecrated the day after Sant Climent, December 11, 1123, by the same bishop. More modest, rougher, but the atmosphere is unique: surrounded by its cemetery, encircled by medieval houses. The nave holds a reproduction of the original apsidal paintings, including the characteristic Lombard orant. Difference in personality from Sant Climent: Santa Maria has remained the village's living center, still used for worship.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "Sant Joan de Boí, in the village of Boí 3 km away, preserves more than the others the architecture of the valley's first construction phase—11th century. Three naves, three apses, medieval paving. The original paintings—known as the \"Bestiary paintings\"—are at the MNAC, but the church has a raw, almost prehistoric presence you don't find elsewhere. For Romanesque architecture enthusiasts, it's the most archaic of the nine.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Santa Eulàlia d'Erill la Vall, right next to the Centre del Romànic, possesses one of the valley's most elegant bell towers—six stories, square plan, like Sant Climent and Sant Joan. This is where the Erill workshop, the sculptural school that carved the famous Descent from the Cross whose originals are at the MNAC and the Episcopal Museum of Vic, worked. On site, a polychrome wooden copy reconstructs the ensemble: Christ, Nicodemus, Joseph of Arimathea, Virgin, Saint John, two thieves. Moving.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "If you arrive early and have time left in late afternoon, climb to Durro (1,386 m)—the highest of the valley's villages. The church of the Nativitat has a fortified bell tower unique in Catalonia, and the village center has kept a rough medieval atmosphere. Away from the main road, few tourists climb up here. Count 30 minutes for the visit, but especially the view over the entire valley basin.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Evening dinner at the Caldes de Boí thermal baths or in an inn in Barruera—the valley's administrative center. Catalan Pyrenean cuisine classics: olla aranesa (stew), trinxat (mashed potato and cabbage with bacon), duck confit with hazelnut, homemade tarts. The Caldes baths are at 1,500 m altitude—37 springs, temperatures from 4 to 56°C, exploited since Roman times. Possibility of therapeutic bathing during the day.",
