          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Beneath the stalls of Triana Market lie the ruins of a castle that made Europe tremble: the Castillo de San Jorge, seat of the Spanish Holy Office from 1481 to 1785—with an interruption from 1626 to 1639 when the tribunal had to relocate to the Casa de los Tavera due to flooding from the Guadalquivir. Spain's first Inquisition tribunal, the most active, the most brutal. Three hundred years of interrogations, torture, and trials unfolded in these cellars until its definitive transfer in 1785, when the walls were buried beneath the present-day market. Today it's a free basement museum: visible cells, torture instruments, nominal lists of the condemned. Chilling and necessary. Closed Mondays.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Plaza de San Francisco, right in the heart of downtown, is the visible flip side of the Inquisition: here stood Seville's main quemadero, the stake where the Holy Office's condemned were publicly burned. Six pyres in the first year, 1481, which consumed primarily Jewish conversos and later Moriscos. The square today serves as the starting point for Holy Week processions—the pasos emerging with hooded Nazarenos have been passing through since 1521. No plaque mentions the pyres: it's this silence that hits hardest.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 30
            },
            {
              "text": "Triana, the former gypsy and sailor suburb across the Guadalquivir, deserves more than a detour: this is where those expelled from Seville after the 1391 pogroms lived, and where the historic rivalry with 'los de Sevilla' was born. The Iglesia de Santa Ana, the city's first Gothic-Mudéjar church (begun in 1276), houses the Virgin of Hope—Triana's pride during the Madrugá on Good Friday. Calle Betis, along the river, is the place for a fino facing the sunset over La Giralda across the way.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 75
            },
            {
              "text": "The Puente de Triana (Puente de Isabel II), built in 1852 on the model of Paris's Carrousel Bridge, connects Triana to downtown. The city's first fixed bridge—before that, you crossed via a pontoon bridge. At the foot on the Triana side, the Carmen chapel and the Altozano, where statues of bullfighter Juan Belmonte and the flamenco singer stand. Obligatory landmark for Sevillians at aperitif hour.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 20
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Dinner at Casa Morales (calle García de Vinuesa), a taberna open since 1850. Classic atmosphere with barrels of manzanilla lined against the wall, slates for chalking up your tab, hand-sliced Iberian ham. Classic tapas: croquetas, espinacas con garbanzos, montadito de pringá. Gentle prices (15-20 euros per person). No reservations, elbow your way to the bar.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 90
